<br>
This is the temple of the Fates, goddesses three, who decided how long before the eternal sleep would take place.  Although as an immortal, such an even should not, would not happen.  Yet there were things that could also occur, which would be as deadly, for an immortal.<br>
<br>
Hecate had scribed for her future not too long ago.  Usually, such visions were often clouded with uncertainty and numerous probabilites.  Yet with this recent vision, Hecate felt sure that she had glimpsed a possilbe truth.  She foresaw the downfall of the Olympians.  Sometime in the far future, they, the Greek gods, would be forgotten, tossed into the rabble of myths and childhood stories.  What they had accomplished would fade, their greatness eroded, their glory denied.  <br>
<br>
For any immortal, their power stemmed from their worshippers.  The more they had, the greater their strength.  To be forgotten, to be unworshipped, would condemn the enitity into a state of torpor, aform of dreamless sleep where they floated in a place of emptiness, impotent for all time.<br>
<br>
This had scared Hecate.  She had seen a world where magic had been forgotten, diminished to a trickle, where once it had roared and crashed, an elemental force undenied.  Was  this inevitable?  Could this course be changed?  She was working hard at doing just this, but she had to have contingencies, just in case she failed.  That was why she was here today.<br>
<br>
She knew the Fates presided over the Tapestry of Time.  That is her target.  If she could somehow get her hands upon the tapestry, then she could insure her future.  But how to do so is the question.  So she stood outside, wondering again.  If she should fail...that is a thought too scary to contemplate. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/bamazonsunite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hecategoddessofmagic>Hecate Goddess of Magic</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(4/21/03 9:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=313.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://nefaria.com/gallery/1152x864/art/sorceress1152.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Future</span><hr size=1> The entrance to the delapidated temple was covered with thick vines and dirt.  The air was still, lifeless, but Hecate knew better.  The presence of intense magic permeated the environ, and she could tell easily where the origin was.  Deep within lay her goal, but she didn't think it would be easy.  The Fates would know she was here, and whether she was going to be giving access or not would soon be determined.<br>
<br>
She proceeded to walk through, but was immediately rebuffed.  Some sort of invisible field obstructed the entrance.  She placed her hand against the invisible barrier  and she felt tiny sparks travel up along her arms.  It tickled a bit, but did no further harm.  This must be the Fates way of gently yet clearly indicating that they did not want her there.  But Hecate was not going to be deterred.  Her very future may lay within, and the Fate would have to do a whole lot more than this.<br>
<br>
She pushed with her hand, and her hand began to glow.  Starting from a lazy ember-red, the color slowly began to brighten, until her hand became pure white.  Crackles and sparks began to erupt along the once invisible barrier.  As her magic mingled with that of the Fates, it soon became a battle of will.  But Hecate is the mistress of magic, and she would not be denied.  In terms of magic, she reigned supreme.  So while she pushed with her hand, she began calling upon ancient words of magic.  The shield beneath her hand began to squirm, as if alive and uncomfortable.  The vibrations began to increase in intensity until the very foundation of the temple began to quake.  Suddenly the shield erupted.  Shards of disintegrating magic flew in all directions, falling upon the goddess in a golden shower of sparks.  Smiling, Hecate, proceeded onwards.<br>
